==English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|mare|mare, mere|lang=enm}} "mare" from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|mere|mere, miere|lang=ang}} "mare, female horse" from {{proto|Germanic|marhijō|female horse|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|mark(')-|horse|lang=en}}. Akin to {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|meriha|lang=goh}} "mare, female horse" ({{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Mähre|lang=de}} "mare"), {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|merr|lang=non}} "mare, female horse" ({{etyl|da|-}} {{term|mær|lang=da}} "mare"), {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|mearh|lang=ang}} "male horse, steed".

Alternative etymology cites derivation via {{etyl|ang}} ''mere, miere'', from {{proto|Germanic|marhijō}} (cf. Dutch ''[[merrie]]'', German ''[[Mähre]]''), from {{proto|Germanic|marhaz|horse|title=}} (compare Old English {{term|mearh||lang=ang}}), from {{etyl|cel-gau}} ''markos'' (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|march}}), from Iranian ''marikas'' (compare Old Persian ''marikas'' 'male, manly'), from ''maryas'' (compare Avestan ''mairya'' 'man; male animal'); akin to Sanskrit ''máryas'' 'young man; stallion'. More at [[marry]].

